    'summary' => '<p>RESEARCH ARTICLE<br>Experimental Brain Research (2025) 243:127<br>https://doi.org/10.1007/s00221-025-07090-z<br>When considering methods of measuring position sense, <br>there is currently no agreement over the preferred method <br>of choice. This problem was recently addressed by Roach et <br>al. (2023) who studied three commonly employed methods. These were two-arm matching, one-arm pointing and one-<br>arm repositioning. Somewhat unexpectedly, each method <br>produced a significantly different outcome. This led to the <br>question, do we have more than one position sense? We have maintained a continuing interest in position <br>sense over the years and, more recently, become aware that <br>under conditions of weightlessness position sense is dis­<br>turbed (Young et al. 1984; Kenyon and Young 1986; Weber <br>et al. 2020). It has led us to speculate about possible mecha­<br>nisms responsible for the disturbance (Weber and Proske <br>2022; Proske and Weber 2023).</p>',
