    'title' => 'Altered Disc Compression in Children with Idiopathic Low Back',
    'summary' => '<p>Altered Disc Compression in Children with Idiopathic Low Back Pain: An Upright MRI Backpack Study Stephen J. Shymon, BA1, Burt Yaszay, MD2, Jerry R. Dwek, MD3, James A. Proudfoot, MSc4, Michael Donohue, PhD4,5, and Alan R. Hargens, PhD1 1University of California, San Diego, Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, San Diego, CA 2Rady Children’s Hospital and Health Center, Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, San Diego, CA 3Department of Radiology, Rady Children’s Hospital and Health Center, University of California, San Diego, 3020 Children’s Way, San Diego, CA 4University of California, San Diego, Clinical and Translational Research Institute, Biostatistics Core, San Diego, CA 5University of California, San Diego, Division of Biostatistics and Bioinformatics, San Diego, CA Abstract Study Design—This study is a repeated measures design to measure the lumbar spine’s response to common backpack loads in children with idiopathic low back pain (ILBP) using upright MRI. Objective—The purpose of this study is to analyze the lumbar spine’s response to backpack loads with upright MRI in ILBP children in order to compare their results to previously published normal child data under the same conditions. We hypothesize that typical backpack loads will have a different effect on the lumbar spine of normal and ILBP children. Summary of Background Data—Research in normal children shows that backpack loads compress the lumbar IVDs, increase lumbar coronal deformity, and increase pain. Methods—Fifteen pediatric and adolescent patients with ILBP were selected. Patients were excluded if a spinal deformity, an underlying pathology, or known injury was identified. A 0.6T upright MRI scanner imaged...</p>',
