  341 => 
  array (
    'filename' => 'PMC3350920_ers022.pdf',
    'title' => 'ers022 3061..3070',
    'summary' => '<p>Journal of Experimental Botany, Vol. 63, No. 8, pp. 3061–3070, 2012<br>doi:10.1093/jxb/ers022<br>Advance Access publication 29 February, 2012<br>This paper is available online free of all access charges (see http://jxb.oxfordjournals.org/open_access.html for further details)<br>RESEARCH PAPER<br>The 14-3-3 proteins of Arabidopsis regulate root growth and<br>chloroplast development as components of the photosensory<br>system<br>John D. Mayﬁeld*, Anna-Lisa Paul and Robert J. Ferl†<br>Plant Molecular and Cellular Biology Program and Horticultural Sciences Department, Interdisciplinary Center for Biotechnology<br>Research, 1301 Fiﬁeld, PO Box 110690, University of Florida, Gainesville, FL 32611, USA<br>* Present address: Institute of Genome Sciences and Policy, Duke University, Durham NC 27708, USA. y To whom correspondence should be addressed. E-mail: robferl@uﬂ.edu<br>Received 21 November 2011; Revised 12 January 2012; Accepted 13 January 2012<br>Abstract<br>The 14-3-3 proteins speciﬁcally bind a number of client proteins to inﬂuence important pathways, including<br>ﬂowering timing via the photosensory system. For instance, 14-3-3 proteins inﬂuence the photosensory system<br>through interactions with Constans (CO) protein. 14-3-3 associations with the photosensory system were further<br>studied in this investigation using 14-3-3 T-DNA insertion mutants to study root and chloroplast development. The<br>14-3-3 m T-DNA insertion mutant, 14-3-3m-1, had shorter roots than the wild type and the difference in root length<br>could be inﬂuenced by light intensity. The 14-3-3 n T-DNA insertion mutants also had shorter roots, but only when<br>grown under narrow-bandwidth red light.</p>',
