    'title' => 'Synergistic Effects of Weightlessness, Isoproterenol, and Radiation on DNA Damage Response and Cytokine Production in Immune Cells',
    'summary' => '<p> <br>International Journal of <br>Molecular Sciences<br>Article<br>Synergistic Effects of Weightlessness, Isoproterenol,<br>and Radiation on DNA Damage Response and<br>Cytokine Production in Immune Cells<br>Maria Moreno-Villanueva 1,2,*, Alan H. Feiveson 1, Stephanie Krieger 4, AnneMarie Kay Brinda 3,<br>Gudrun von Scheven 2, Alexander Bürkle 2<br>, Brian Crucian 1 and Honglu Wu 1<br>1<br>National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), Johnson Space Center Houston,<br>Houston, TX 77058, USA; alan.h.feiveson@nasa.gov (A.H.F. ); brian.crucian-1@nasa.gov (B.C. );<br>honglu.wu-1@nasa.gov (H.W.) 2<br>Molecular Toxicology Group, Department of Biology, Box 628, University of Konstanz,<br>78457 Konstanz, Germany; gudrun.vonscheven@uni-konstanz.de (G.v.S. );<br>alexander.buerkle@uni-konstanz.de (A.B.) 3<br>Department of Biomedical Engineering, University of Minnesota, 312 Church Street SE,<br>Minneapolis, MN 55455, USA; kovac149@umn.edu<br>4<br>KBRwyle, 2400 NASA Parkway, Houston, TX 77058, USA; stephanie.s.krieger@nasa.gov<br>*<br>Correspondence: maria.moreno-villanueva@uni-konstanz.de or maria.morenovillanueva@nasa.gov;<br>Tel. : +49-7531-88-3599<br>Received: 24 October 2018; Accepted: 11 November 2018; Published: 21 November 2018<br><br><br>Abstract: The implementation of rotating-wall vessels (RWVs) for studying the effect of lack of gravity<br>has attracted attention, especially in the ﬁelds of stem cells, tissue regeneration, and cancer research. Immune cells incubated in RWVs exhibit several features of immunosuppression including impaired<br>leukocyte proliferation, cytokine responses, and antibody production. Interestingly, stress hormones<br>inﬂuence cellular immune pathways affected by microgravity, such as cell proliferation, apoptosis,<br>DNA repair, and T cell activation. These pathways are crucial defense mechanisms that protect the cell<br>from toxins, pathogens, and radiation.</p>',
