    'filename' => 'PP_PP201600173R1.pdf',
    'title' => 'ppPP201600173R1 833..848',
    'summary' => '<p>Pectin Methylesteriﬁcation Impacts the<br>Relationship between Photosynthesis and<br>Plant Growth1[OPEN]<br>Sarathi M. Weraduwage, Sang-Jin Kim, Luciana Renna, Fransisca C. Anozie, Thomas D. Sharkey*, and<br>Federica Brandizzi*<br>Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology (S.M.W., F.C.A., T.D.S. ); Department of Energy Plant<br>Research Laboratory (S.-J.K., L.R., F.B. ); Department of Energy Great Lakes Bioenergy Research Center (S.-J.K.,<br>F.B. ); and Department of Plant Biology (F.B. ), Michigan State University, East Lansing, Michigan 48824<br>ORCID IDs: 0000-0002-0591-4210 (S.M.W. ); 0000-0002-4423-3223 (T.D.S.). Photosynthesis occurs in mesophyll cells of specialized organs such as leaves. The rigid cell wall encapsulating photosynthetic<br>cells controls the expansion and distribution of cells within photosynthetic tissues. The relationship between photosynthesis and<br>plant growth is affected by leaf area. However, the underlying genetic mechanisms affecting carbon partitioning to different<br>aspects of leaf growth are not known.</p>',
